<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<meta charset="utf-8" />
		<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width" />
		<title>Monster Classifications - Untamed Bestiary</title>
	</head>
	<body>
		<nav class="nav">
			<div class="container">
				<a href="/" class="logo">UNTAMED</a>
				<div class="nav-links">
					<a href="/rules">Rules</a>
					<a href="/quick-reference">Quick Reference</a>
					<a href="/character">Characters</a>
					<a href="/bestiary">Bestiary</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</nav>

		<main>
			<div class="container">
				<div class="breadcrumb">
					<a href="/bestiary">‚Üê Back to Bestiary</a>
				</div>

				<header class="page-header">
					<div class="icon">üêæ</div>
					<h1>Monster Classifications</h1>
					<p class="subtitle">Understanding the Roles of the Wild</p>
				</header>

				<article class="content">
					<section class="intro-section">
						<blockquote>
							"Every creature in the wild fills a role ‚Äî predator, prey, parasite, or god.
							When you understand what it eats, what it fears, and what it protects, you understand how to hunt it."
						</blockquote>
						<p>Monster classifications exist to help GMs design encounters that feel ecologically grounded. Each classification defines how a creature behaves, evolves, and interacts with the environment and the hunt loop.</p>
					</section>

					<!-- STANDARD CLASSIFICATIONS -->
					<section class="classification-tier">
						<div class="tier-header">
							<h2>üêæ Standard Classifications</h2>
							<p>These creatures form the majority of the ecosystem ‚Äî from small prey to apex-level hunters. They populate most hunts and define the ecological identity of each biome.</p>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Beast Rodents</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Skittish scavengers or opportunists at the base of the food chain.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Small-to-medium size, quick breeding, tunneling, or nest-building behavior.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Skirmisher, Ambusher (burrow), Pack, Tool User.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Excellent "sign creatures" ‚Äî their absence signals larger predators nearby.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Beast Birds</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Aerial hunters and scavengers that define the vertical layers of a biome.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Flight, dive attacks, keen eyesight, social nesting behaviors.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Flyer, Kiter, Skirmisher.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Great for multi-level arenas and high-ground control; use to teach players about visibility and range management.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Fanged Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Agile mammalian predators that stalk or ambush prey using precision and instinct.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> High DEX or INS, bleed mechanics, stealth, territorial aggression.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Ambusher, Pack/Tactician, Brute (for apex species).
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Use fanged beasts to showcase stamina attrition and tracking pressure over time.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Reptile Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Scaled predators ‚Äî from serpentine hunters to lumbering lizards.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Armor plating, venom, cold-blooded endurance, or regenerative abilities.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Brute, Debuffer, Guardian.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Excellent middle-tier monsters that emphasize environmental adaptation (heat, moisture, or sun exposure).
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Amphibian Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Dual-environment predators of wetlands and caves.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Regeneration when wet, toxin-dispersal, long leaps, and camouflage.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Debuffer, Ambusher, Swimmer.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Create stamina pressure through terrain ‚Äî mud, water, and heat.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Crustacean Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Hard-shelled, water-adjacent titans.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Armor layers, pincer grabs, burrowing, tidal adaptation.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Guardian, Brute, Shifter (terrain control via water or sand).
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Introduce multi-stage armor breaks and environmental hazards (floods, tidal shifts).
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Insectoids</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Hive-based creatures acting in coordinated swarms or colonies.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Carapace armor, venom, pheromone signaling, hive intelligence.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Support, Pack, Guardian (queen), Debuffer.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Great for dynamic battlefield spawns or multi-target encounters; the hive acts like a single living machine.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Myriapod Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Multi-segmented hunters that thrive in rotlines and caverns.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Segmented armor, caustic secretions, rapid bursts, tremor-sense.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Ambusher, Brute, Debuffer.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Use vibration tracking and close-quarters movement to create claustrophobic tension.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Plant Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Living flora or symbiotic plant-life; ambush predators of the forest floor.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Rooted or slow movement, toxin release, camouflage, regenerative growth.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Guardian, Shifter, Debuffer.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Great for corruption arcs or "territory fights" where the ground itself becomes the enemy.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Cephalopod / Tentacled Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Ambush predators of the deep ‚Äî clever, fluid, and alien in motion.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Camouflage, multi-limb grapples, ink/silt blinds, tool use, nerve-ring weak spots.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Tool User, Ambusher, Swimmer.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Use as "smart predators" ‚Äî dynamic repositioning and problem-solving mid-hunt.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Parasitic / Brood Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Macro-parasites or egg-spawning horrors that dominate hosts or spread plagues.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Host control, fatigue drain, brood swarms, vulnerability to fire/salt.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Debuffer, Support, Tactician (hive logic).
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Ideal for multi-phase horror hunts ‚Äî where the threat multiplies over time.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Primal Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Dinosaur-like or ancient monsters ‚Äî living echoes of a forgotten era.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Massive bodies, relentless aggression, instinctive resilience.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Brute, Guardian, Shifter.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Set-piece hunts ‚Äî terrain-smashing monsters that define a biome's identity.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Drakes</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Dragonkin, lesser cousins of the Elder Dragons ‚Äî intelligent, territorial, fierce.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Elemental breath, semi-flight, predatory cunning.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Flyer, Brute, Tactician.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> High-level single-target fights emphasizing timing and positional play.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Leviathans</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Colossal water or semi-aquatic predators ruling the lakes, rivers, and coasts.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Immense stamina, environmental control (waves, currents), amphibious combat.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Swimmer, Shifter, Brute.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Thematic biome bosses ‚Äî treat water as a living hazard and time pressure as their weapon.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card">
							<h3>Aberrant Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Mutations and anomalies ‚Äî nature's corruption or alchemical byproduct.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Mutation mid-fight, warped anatomy, psychic dissonance.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Shifter, Debuffer, Intelligent (learned behavior).
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Perfect for "what the hell is that" moments ‚Äî unpredictable tempo shifts and sanity-threatening behavior.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
					</section>

					<!-- APEX CLASSIFICATIONS -->
					<section class="classification-tier apex">
						<div class="tier-header">
							<h2>üåã Apex Classifications</h2>
							<p>These are the biome rulers ‚Äî monsters that don't just live in ecosystems but define them. Their existence reshapes migration, weather, and even geography. They are the campaign's punctuation marks.</p>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card apex-card">
							<h3>Elder Beasts</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Apex predators evolved into sentient territorial forces.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Elemental resistance, supernatural awareness, adaptive AI.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Brute + Intelligent + Guardian.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Use Elder Beasts as living bosses ‚Äî entities that remember prior encounters and adapt across sessions.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card apex-card">
							<h3>Elder Brutes</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Colossi that reshape terrain simply by moving.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Immense mass, seismic movement, devastating area effects.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Brute + Shifter.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> Set them against the environment itself ‚Äî cliff collapses, landslides, collapsing biomes. Each hit should change the map.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>

						<div class="classification-card apex-card">
							<h3>Elder Dragons</h3>
							<div class="classification-content">
								<div class="profile">
									<strong>Profile:</strong> Living cataclysms. Their mere existence alters weather, magic, and balance.
								</div>
								<div class="traits">
									<strong>Common Traits:</strong> Elemental mastery, unbreakable will, transcendent intelligence.
								</div>
								<div class="archetypes">
									<strong>Behavior Archetypes:</strong> Intelligent + Flyer + Shifter + Guardian.
								</div>
								<div class="gm-use">
									<strong>GM Use:</strong> The culmination of the ecosystem ‚Äî their death or survival rewrites the world's state. Treat them like gods in motion, not just HP pools.
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
					</section>

				</article>
			</div>
		</main>

		<style>
			* { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
			:root {
				--forest-dark: #1a2e1a; --forest-green: #2d5016; --moss-green: #4a7c2f;
				--leaf-green: #6b9d3a; --amber: #d4a257; --earth-brown: #5c4033;
				--cream: #f5f1e8; --text-light: #e8e4d8;
				--apex-red: #8b2e2e;
			}
			body { font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, sans-serif; background: var(--forest-dark); color: var(--text-light); line-height: 1.7; min-height: 100vh; }
			.container { max-width: 1200px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 2rem; }

			.nav { background: var(--forest-green); border-bottom: 2px solid var(--amber); padding: 1rem 0; position: sticky; top: 0; z-index: 100; }
			.nav .container { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; }
			.logo { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 900; color: var(--amber); text-decoration: none; letter-spacing: 0.2rem; }
			.nav-links { display: flex; gap: 2rem; }
			.nav-links a { color: var(--cream); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 500; transition: color 0.3s; }
			.nav-links a:hover { color: var(--amber); }

			.breadcrumb { padding: 2rem 0 1rem; }
			.breadcrumb a { color: var(--leaf-green); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 500; }
			.breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--amber); }

			.page-header { padding: 2rem 0 3rem; text-align: center; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--amber); margin-bottom: 3rem; }
			.icon { font-size: 5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
			.page-header h1 { font-size: 3rem; color: var(--amber); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
			.subtitle { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--leaf-green); font-style: italic; }

			.content { padding-bottom: 4rem; }

			.intro-section { background: var(--forest-green); padding: 2rem; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 3rem; border: 2px solid var(--earth-brown); }
			.intro-section blockquote { font-style: italic; border-left: 4px solid var(--amber); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--leaf-green); font-size: 1.1rem; }
			.intro-section p { margin: 0; }

			.classification-tier { margin-bottom: 4rem; }
			.classification-tier.apex .tier-header { border-left-color: var(--apex-red); }
			.tier-header { background: var(--moss-green); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 2rem; border-left: 4px solid var(--amber); }
			.tier-header h2 { color: var(--amber); font-size: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
			.tier-header p { margin: 0; }

			.classification-card { background: var(--forest-green); padding: 2rem; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; border: 2px solid var(--earth-brown); transition: border-color 0.3s; }
			.classification-card:hover { border-color: var(--amber); }
			.classification-card.apex-card { border-color: var(--apex-red); border-width: 3px; }
			.classification-card.apex-card:hover { border-color: var(--amber); }

			.classification-card h3 { color: var(--amber); font-size: 1.75rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-bottom: 0.75rem; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--earth-brown); }
			.classification-card.apex-card h3 { color: var(--apex-red); }

			.classification-content > div { margin-bottom: 1rem; padding: 0.75rem; border-radius: 6px; }
			.classification-content > div:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

			.profile { background: var(--forest-dark); }
			.traits { background: var(--forest-dark); }
			.archetypes { background: var(--forest-dark); }
			.gm-use { background: var(--moss-green); border-left: 3px solid var(--leaf-green); }

			.classification-content strong { color: var(--amber); font-weight: 600; }

			@media (max-width: 768px) {
				.nav .container { flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem; }
				.nav-links { gap: 1rem; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center; }
				.page-header h1 { font-size: 2rem; }
			}

			html { scroll-behavior: smooth; }
		</style>
	</body>
</html>
